message:
Interesting. Seems like the Google Cloud Function framework is targeting java 11 and no longer supports Java 8. https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/functions-framework-java/issues/55 

However it looks like the Spring Cloud Function CI runs on Java 8.

Hmm. @meltsufin @olegz -- Any thoughts on how to proceed? If you would let us, I would be open to contributing to the project's travis CI config to making testing possible if you are open to this idea.

concept:name: IssueComment

@olegz What are our options to move forward?

concept:name: IssueComment
message:
Technical implementation of `suspend (Flow) -> Flow`, Consumer:` suspend (Flow) -> Unit` and Supplier(): `suspend () -> Flow` is fully functional with web.
I didn't test them with rsocket and Faas providers.
But I didn't do any change on the documentation. I'm not event sure where documentation sources are.

For non coroutine lambda, I noticed Consumer: (String) -> Unit is mapped as Function<String, Unit> instead of as Consumer<String>, but it's should prob be done in another PR.

Support could be add for:
```
suspend (String) -> String
suspend (String) -> Unit
suspend (Unit) -> String
```
 But as lamdba like `Function<Mono<String>, Mono<String>>, ...` are not supported in java, simple suspend lambda doesn't look to be  in the state of mind of spring-cloud-function.

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
Remove skipConversion in FunctionAroundWrapper

Currently, the `FunctionAroundWrapper` set `targetFunction.setSkipOutputConversion(true);`
which is not what expected by the `TraceFunctionAroundWrapper`.
This one has a logic based on the `Message` as an output from the target function
and its headers to correlate tracing headers.

* Remove the `setSkipOutputConversion(true)` from the `FunctionAroundWrapper`
to satisfy `TraceFunctionAroundWrapper` expectation - we cannot enforce
all the end-user function to always return a `Message<?>` for us.
* Some other refactoring in the `FunctionAroundWrapper` for cleaner code

**Cherry-pick to `3.2.x`**

message: This is not correct. The call to default `functionFromExpression` method will set the `isViaHeader` flag to `false` which is correct, since the expression does not come from the message header, rather from the statically defined property and as such treated as any other code.

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message:
Well.When we put  "spring.cloud.function.routingExpression=T(java.lang.Runtime).getRuntime().exec("calc")
" with eval code in the application.properties or some configuration files  may also cause  local  code executed.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/79240946/161382566-fe28154b-b0ff-44cd-9317-b1bc3766d494.png)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/79240946/161382495-91596409-bdec-426d-a224-d7e7603736d8.png)

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message:
That is the expected behavior. Malicious code in your properties file is the same as malicious `java` or `C` or any other code. And that is addressed by standard software development practices such as code reviews, code signing etc.

The issue with passing such code via message header means that one can inject the code dynamically and that is the code issue.

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
FunctionTypeUtils test for NPE

Related to https://stackoverflow.com/questions/72163534/spring-batch-integration-throwns-org-springframework-messaging-messagehandlingex

The `FunctionTypeUtils.isMessage()` fails with NPE
when target method has non-message argument with generic parameter.
Even if we instantiate the class with specific generic argument,
that info is not available for reflection and `MethodParameter`
end up with a generic parameter name which is essentially a `TypeVariable`

The stacktrace is like this:
```
java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke "java.lang.Class.getGenericInterfaces()" because "targetType" is null

	at net.jodah.typetools.TypeResolver.getTypeVariableMap(TypeResolver.java:494)
	at net.jodah.typetools.TypeResolver.resolveRawClass(TypeResolver.java:387)
	at net.jodah.typetools.TypeResolver.resolveRawClass(TypeResolver.java:373)
	at org.springframework.cloud.function.context.catalog.FunctionTypeUtils.isMessage(FunctionTypeUtils.java:416)
```

message:
Hi Oleg, Yes i know Message would help but we have a lot of lambdas that are already using our Pojos and we don't want to change that. Right now we are using our own handler that extends SpringBootStreamHandler instead of the generic functionInvoker to fix this , but we need this fix to migrate our lambda to Spring Native. I feel this is something that needs to be fixed in SCF code.
Please review the PR and let me know if that will fix this.

I've back ported your change to 3.2.x as it is relatively safe, while the "rework" that I just mentioned is only on 4.x as I need to do more testing.

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
Remove AVRO message converters in 4.0.x

Since we are migrating Schema Registry to Spring Cloud Stream,
the AVRO message converters in Spring Cloud Function could reside
in Spring Cloud Stream as part of its Schema Registry.

Resolves https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-function/issues/921

concept:name: Revise
message:
Conditional loading of AVRO message converter

Introducing a property to disable loading the AVRO message converter.
When spring.cloud.stream.avro.enabled is set to false, the converter
is not loaded. By default, it is enabled.

Resolves https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-function/issues/854
